\section{Conclusion}
\label{sec:conclusion}

In this paper, we have presented the CLIP-Enhanced Semantic Manifold Diffusion (CESM-Diff) framework, a novel generative approach specifically designed to address the critical challenge of zero-shot fault diagnosis in modern, highly integrated industrial systems. One of the primary contributions of this work is the departure from traditional, human-defined binary attribute vectors, which often fail to capture the complex physical relationships inherent in equipment failure modes. By integrating the Contrastive Language-Image Pretraining (CLIP) text encoder into the zero-shot learning (ZSL) pipeline, our method extracts continuous, high-dimensional semantic embeddings from diverse natural language fault descriptions. This approach leverages the extensive linguistic and visual-alignment knowledge base embedded within CLIP to provide a more robust and flexible foundation for semantic modeling.

Our proposed dual-path diffusion architecture, featuring a specialized bidirectional cross-path attention mechanism, ensures tight and stable alignment between sensor-derived vibration features and their corresponding textual semantics throughout the entire denoising process. Furthermore, the introduction of Semantic Manifold Interpolation (SMI) enables the effective synthesis of highly discriminative features for unseen fault classes by accurately modeling the continuous latent manifold of the vibration data, thereby bridging the diagnostic gap between seen and unseen domains.

Our extensive experimental evaluation across three diverse industrial benchmarks---the Tennessee Eastman Process (TEP), a complex Hydraulic System monitoring dataset, and the CWRU Bearing dataset---demonstrates that CESM-Diff consistently and significantly outperforms existing state-of-the-art zero-shot learning and generative methods. These results confirm that our framework effectively mitigates the persistent domain shift problem and substantially enhances the diagnostic accuracy for novel failure modes that were entirely absent during the training phase.

Despite the promising performance presented in this study, the current work has certain limitations that provide fertile ground for future research. Future iterations could explore the integration of Large Language Models (LLMs) to automatically generate more diverse diagnostic metadata directly from unstructured maintenance logs and expert reports. Additionally, extending the dual-path diffusion process to handle highly non-stationary and time-varying industrial environments remains a challenging frontier. We also plan to investigate the integration of physics-informed constraints into the manifold interpolation and denoising stages to ensure that synthesized fault features strictly adhere to established mechanical degradation laws.

In conclusion, the development of semantic-aware generative models that can bridge the gap between human language and industrial sensor data represents a significant step toward the realization of more autonomous and intelligent industrial diagnostic systems in the era of Industry 4.0.

